<h2 id="readme">README</h2>

<p>In October, the Library of Congress published a <a href="https://blogs.loc.gov/law/2022/09/introducing-the-congress-gov-api/">Congress.gov application programming interface</a>. Using this API, we created House of Representatives, Senate and member profiles pages on <a href="https://usa.govfresh.com">USA.GovFresh</a>.</p>

<h2 id="data">Data</h2>

<p>Data used for this project:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://api.congress.gov/">api.congress.gov</a></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="repo">Repo</h2>

<p>Official repository:</p>

<ul>
  <li>/<a href="https://github.com/LibraryOfCongress">LibraryOfCongress</a>/<a href="https://github.com/LibraryOfCongress/api.congress.gov">api.congress.gov</a></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="issues">Issues</h2>

<p>Issues we submitted:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/LibraryOfCongress/api.congress.gov/issues/33">CORS error</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/LibraryOfCongress/api.congress.gov/issues/50">Sponsored legislation API URL not correct?</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/LibraryOfCongress/api.congress.gov/issues/53">Improve member photo quality</a></li>
</ul>

<h2 id="kudos">Kudos</h2>

<p>Big kudos to the Library of Congress for:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Creating a public API.</li>
  <li>Creating a public repository.</li>
  <li>Openly and actively engaging with the public.</li>
</ul>

